# Template Standardization Standards

Standards for template standardization and consistency based on learnings from mobile navbar implementation.

<rule>
name: template_standardization
description: Standards for template standardization and consistency
filters:
  - type: file_extension
    pattern: "\\.(html|jinja|template)$"
  - type: content
    pattern: "(template|jinja|html|header|nav)"

actions:
  - type: suggest
    message: |
      ## Template Standardization Standards

      ### 1. Consistent Structure
      - Use identical HTML structure for shared components across templates
      - Maintain consistent class naming conventions
      - Follow the same pattern for similar functionality

      ### 2. Context-Aware Navigation
      - Implement dynamic navigation based on user state
      - Use Jinja logic to show appropriate navigation items
      - Highlight active page in navigation

      ### 3. Component Reusability
      - Extract shared components to avoid duplication
      - Use consistent patterns for similar UI elements
      - Maintain template-specific styling where appropriate

      ### 4. Template-Specific Considerations
      - Preserve unique functionality while standardizing shared elements
      - Ensure template-specific JavaScript doesn't conflict with shared components
      - Maintain individual template aesthetics and branding

      ### 5. Documentation
      - Document template-specific requirements and considerations
      - Maintain clear separation between shared and unique components
      - Update documentation when templates are modified

examples:
  - input: |
      <!-- Bad: Inconsistent structure across templates -->
      <!-- Template 1 -->
      <div class="navbar">
        <a href="/" class="logo">Logo</a>
        <div class="nav-links">...</div>
      </div>

      <!-- Template 2 -->
      <header class="header">
        <span class="brand">Logo</span>
        <nav class="navigation">...</nav>
      </header>

      <!-- Good: Consistent structure -->
      <!-- Template 1 & 2 -->
      <div class="header-bar">
        <a href="/" class="batch-link">Logo</a>
        <nav class="navbar">...</nav>
      </div>
    output: "Use consistent HTML structure for shared components across templates"

  - input: |
      <!-- Bad: Hardcoded navigation -->
      <nav class="navbar">
        <a href="/login">LOGIN</a>
        <a href="/signup">SIGN UP</a>
      </nav>

      <!-- Good: Context-aware navigation -->
      <nav class="navbar">
        {% if session.user %}
          <a href="/download">DOWNLOAD</a>
          <a href="/upload">UPLOAD</a>
          <a href="/logout">LOGOUT</a>
        {% else %}
          <a href="/login">LOGIN</a>
          <a href="/signup">SIGN UP</a>
        {% endif %}
      </nav>
    output: "Implement context-aware navigation using Jinja logic"

  - input: |
      <!-- Bad: Template-specific styling mixed with shared components -->
      <div class="header-bar" style="background: red; padding: 20px;">
        <a href="/" class="logo">Logo</a>
      </div>

      <!-- Good: Separated concerns -->
      <div class="header-bar">
        <a href="/" class="logo">Logo</a>
      </div>
      <style>
        /* Template-specific styles */
        .header-bar { background: red; padding: 20px; }
      </style>
    output: "Separate shared components from template-specific styling"

metadata:
  priority: high
  version: 1.0
  tags: ["template", "standardization", "consistency", "jinja"]
</rule>
description:
globs:
alwaysApply: false
---
